[A prior ProMED-mail post (Syphilis - USA (11): (OH) MSM, congenital, rising incidence, RFI 20141006.2837388) reported that there was a rising incidence of syphilis in Franklin County, Ohio, in men who have sex with men (MSM), some of whom also had wives and girlfriends, which contributed to the concurrent rising incidence of congenital syphilis. The news report above adds that the increase in cases of syphilis is occurring among young MSM who are disproportionately African-American and is accompanied by an increase in cases among women.

In many localities, the increased incidence of syphilis occurring in MSM has been characterized by high rates of human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) co-infection. If this pattern is occurring in Franklin County, there may also be also an increase in the incidence of congenital HIV infection. ProMED-mail would appreciate more information on the syphilis outbreak in Ohio from a knowledgeable source.

Franklin County, with a population of 1 212 263 in 2013, is located in the center of the U.S. state of Ohio; its county seat is the city of Columbus (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Franklin_County,_Ohio). - Mod.ML

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3535758,237.]
